4, 2011|last=King|first=Susan|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=June 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610172449/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-xpm-2011-sep-04-la-ca-sneaks-puss-20110904-story.html|archive-date=June 10, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and \"the world's greatest feline swordfighter\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2015/12/netflixdreamworks-preview-adventures-of-puss-in-boots-season-2-122455/|title=Netflix/Dreamworks Preview \"Adventures of Puss in Boots\" Season 2|date=December 11, 2015|last=Beck|first=Jerry|website=[[IndieWire]]|access-date=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730155629/https://www.indiewire.com/2015/12/netflixdreamworks-preview-adventures-of-puss-in-boots-season-2-122455/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Jerry Beck}}</ref> He was also regarded as \"smooth-talking\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/puss-in-boots-reboot-spider-man-into-the-spider-verse-director-1203150405/|title='Puss in Boots' Sequel Lands 'Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse' Director|date=February 26, 2019|last=McNary|first=Dave|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=April 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416192039/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/puss-in-boots-reboot-spider-man-into-the-spider-verse-director-1203150405/|archive-date=April 16, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=PopMatters>{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/150617-puss-in-boots-2495924422.html|title='Puss in Boots': That's One Fine Looking Cat|date=October 27, 2011|last=Hassenger|first=Jesse|magazine=[[PopMatters]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630142921/https://www.popmatters.com/150617-puss-in-boots-2495924422.html|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"heroic\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://celebrity.nine.com.au/movies/kids-movies-school-holidays-stan-new-kung-fu-panda-shrek-madagasgar/ed786b4b-48b2-4fdd-9252-4cd0aef73f6e|title=The best movies to stream for the kids these school holidays|date=September 20, 2019|last=Knight|first=Claire|website=[[Nine.com.au]]|access-date=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925135128/https://celebrity.nine.com.au/movies/kids-movies-school-holidays-stan-new-kung-fu-panda-shrek-madagasgar/ed786b4b-48b2-4fdd-9252-4cd0aef73f6e|archive-date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"honorable\",<ref name=TheNewYorkTimes3>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/05/18/movies/film-review-the-new-son-in-law-s-an-ogre-and-hollywood-is-the-target.html|title=Film Review; The New Son-in-Law's an Ogre, And Hollywood Is the Target|date=May 18, 2004|last=Scott|first=A. O.|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=June 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606211812/https://www.nytimes.com/2004/05/18/movies/film-review-the-new-son-in-law-s-an-ogre-and-hollywood-is-the-target.html|archive-date=June 6, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=A. O. Scott}}</ref> self-confident,<ref name=Empire2>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/50-greatest-animated-characters/?film=21/|title=The 50 Best Animated Movie Characters|date=November 8, 2010|magazine=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704104531/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/50-greatest-animated-characters/?film=21%2F|archive-date=July 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"passionate\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2011/10/27/puss_in_boots_good_kitty.html|title=Puss in Boots: Good kitty|date=October 27, 2011|last=Barnard|first=Linda|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=September 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905215524/https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2011/10/27/puss_in_boots_good_kitty.html|archive-date=September 5, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> loyal,<ref name=Empire2/> with \"humble\" origins.<ref name=Quickflix/> ''[[Collider (website)|Collider]]''{{'}}s Christina Radish described Puss as \"charming and unforgettable\", adding that he \"was a cat destined for great things\".<ref name=Collider/> Radish said that Puss getting his own film was no surprise, commenting that the character has a \"tremendous heart\",<ref name=Collider/> and is a \"much-loved fighter\".<ref name=Collider5/> ''[[Fantasy Magazine]]''{{'}}s Andrew Penn Romine called Puss \"equal parts rogue and hero\",<ref name=FantasyMagazine/> but [[Stephen Holden]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' described the character as \"this vain, spoiled, swashbuckler\".<ref name=TheNewYorkTimes4>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/28/movies/puss-in-boots-with-antonio-banderas-review.html|title=A Fairy Tale Mix With 9 Lives and Dozens of Egg Jokes|date=October 27, 2011|last=Holden|first=Stephen|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630143212/https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/28/movies/puss-in-boots-with-antonio-banderas-review.html|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Stephen Holden}}</ref> According to Holden, Puss is not \"as clear-cut a personality [in ''Puss in Boots''] as he was\" in the ''Shrek'' films.<ref name=TheNewYorkTimes4/> ''IndieLondon''{{'}}s Rob Carnevale called him a \"cheeky feline swashbuckler\" and ''Puss in Boots''{{'}}s \"enigmatic central character\".<ref name=IndieLondon3/> [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' described Puss as a \"dashing little kitty centerstage\", \"ever-bold\",<ref name=TheHollywoodReporter2>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/puss-boots-film-review-252312|title=Puss in Boots: Film Review|date=October 23, 2011|last=McCarthy|first=Todd|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630144354/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/puss-boots-film-review-252312|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Todd McCarthy}}</ref> and \"a self-deprecating, sometimes bumbling but ultimately dashing swordsman\".<ref name=TheHollywoodReporter2/> McCarthy enjoyed Puss's \"vigorous physicality\" in ''Puss in Boots''.<ref name=TheHollywoodReporter2/> [[Neil Genzlinger]] of ''The New York Times'' called Puss \"endearing\", \"dashing and fearless but also a tad reckless\".<ref name=TheNewYorkTimes2/> Chrissy Iley of ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' described him as \"the world's most seductive animated cat\".<ref name=TheTelegraph/> ''[[IGN]]''{{'}}s Andy Patrizio enjoyed Puss in ''Shrek 2'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/11/06/shrek-2|title=Shrek 2|date=November 5, 2004|last=Patrizio|first=Andy|website=[[IGN]]|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706083402/http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/11/06/shrek-2|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and Scott Collura of the same website said that Puss \"remains dignified and cool\" in ''Shrek Forever After'' despite his weight gain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/05/21/shrek-forever-after-review|title=Shrek Forever After Review|date=May 20, 2010|last=Collura|first=Scott|website=[[IGN]]|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706090101/http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/05/21/shrek-forever-after-review|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The character has been regarded as a source of comic relief.<ref name=TheIndependent>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/film-trailer-banderas-in-shrek-spin-off-puss-in-boots-2234830.html|title=Film trailer: Banderas in 'Shrek' spin-off 'Puss in Boots'|date=March 7, 2011|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|access-date=July 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828131601/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/film-trailer-banderas-in-shrek-spin-off-puss-in-boots-2234830.html|archive-date=August 28, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=TheHollywoodReporter/><ref name=PopMatters/><ref name=TheNational>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/cat-in-boots-in-3d-1.608075|title=Cat in Boots in 3D|date=November 24, 2011|last=Mottram|first=James|newspaper=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630144945/https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/cat-in-boots-in-3d-1.608075|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCritics have stated that Puss is similar to Zorro,<ref name=TheAtlantic>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/10/how-celebrities-took-over-cartoon-voice-acting/247481/|title=How Celebrities Took Over Cartoon Voice Acting|date=October 28, 2011|last=Meslow|first=Scott|magazine=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=July 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731120907/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/10/how-celebrities-took-over-cartoon-voice-acting/247481/|archive-date=July 31, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=Variety>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2004/film/awards/shrek-2-2-1200533426/|title=Shrek 2|date=May 15, 2004|last=McCarthy|first=Todd|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704015401/https://variety.com/2004/film/awards/shrek-2-2-1200533426/|archive-date=July 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Todd McCarthy}}</ref><ref name=Empire>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/shrek-2/review/|title=Shrek 2 Review|date=July 29, 2016|last=Errigo|first=Angie|magazine=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704001459/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/shrek-2/review/|archive-date=July 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=TheGuardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/News_Story/Critic_Review/Guardian_Film_of_the_week/0,,1251483,00.html|title=Shrek 2|date=July 2, 2004|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704000511/https://www.theguardian.com/film/News_Story/Critic_Review/Guardian_Film_of_the_week/0,,1251483,00.html|archive-date=July 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Peter Bradshaw}}</ref><ref name=IGN/><ref name=GulfNews/> and he was called \"a glorious reimagining of the swashbuckling charm of Zorro\".<ref name=Empire2/> Reviewers have also said that Puss resembles [[Jack Sparrow|Captain Jack Sparrow]] from the film series ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean (film series)|Pirates of the Caribbean]]'',<ref name=TheDenverPost>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2011/10/26/movie-review-puss-in-boots-plies-its-puns-with-catlike-dexterity/|title=Movie review: \"Puss in Boots\" plies its puns with catlike dexterity|date=October 26, 2011|last=Kennedy|first=Lisa|magazine=[[The Denver Post]]|access-date=August 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829180128/https://www.denverpost.com/2011/10/26/movie-review-puss-in-boots-plies-its-puns-with-catlike-dexterity/|archive-date=August 29, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=TimeOut>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/puss-in-boots|title=Puss in Boots|date=December 6, 2011|last=Smith|first=Anna|magazine=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|access-date=August 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829171456/https://www.timeout.com/london/film/puss-in-boots|archive-date=August 29, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> because of him being a \"swashbuckling\",<ref name=TheDenverPost/> \"charismatic scene-stealer\".<ref name=TimeOut/> Puss has also been commented to share similarities with the characters [[Don Juan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vancouversun.com/Movie+Review+Puss+Boots/5622441/story.html|title=Movie Review: Puss in Boots|date=October 28, 2011|last=Monk|first=Katherine|newspaper=[[Vancouver Sun]]|access-date=September 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926194031/http://www.vancouversun.com/Movie+Review+Puss+Boots/5622441/story.html|archive-date=September 26, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gqindia.com/content/review-puss-boots/|title=Review: Puss in Boots|date=December 1, 2011|last=Sirota|first=Peggy|magazine=[[GQ (Indian edition)|GQ]]|access-date=September 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926190631/https://www.gqindia.com/content/review-puss-boots/|archive-date=September 26, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2011/10/puss-in-boots-movie-review-180901/|title=Puss In Boots\u2014movie review|date=October 28, 2011|last=Maltin|first=Leonard|website=[[IndieWire]]|access-date=September 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926194456/https://www.indiewire.com/2011/10/puss-in-boots-movie-review-180901/|archive-date=September 26, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all|author-link=Leonard Maltin}}</ref> [[Pep\u00e9 Le Pew]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bayweekly.com/articles/movie-reviews/article/puss-boots?page=3|title=Puss in Boots|last=Beechener|first=Diana|website=Annapolis Bay Weekly|access-date=September 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926203150/http://www.bayweekly.com/articles/movie-reviews/article/puss-boots?page=3|archive-date=September 26, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/look-whos-talking-in-the-movies-greatest-cartoons-2304904.html|title=Look who's talking in the movies' greatest cartoons|date=July 1, 2011|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|access-date=September 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926212025/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/look-whos-talking-in-the-movies-greatest-cartoons-2304904.html|archive-date=September 26, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/events/film/2011-10-28/puss-in-boots/|title=Puss in Boots|date=October 28, 2011|last=Baumgarten|first=Marjorie|newspaper=[[The Austin Chronicle]]|access-date=September 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926212949/https://www.austinchronicle.com/events/film/2011-10-28/puss-in-boots/|archive-date=September 26, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and [[Tarzan]].<ref name=TheTelegraph2>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/lifestyle/pets/10457167/Pet-tales-Zorro-the-cat.html|title=Pet tales: Zorro the cat|date=November 19, 2013|last=Forbes|first=Derek|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=September 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926203849/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/lifestyle/pets/10457167/Pet-tales-Zorro-the-cat.html|archive-date=September 26, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe character's design has been discussed and praised, with Jesse Hassenger of ''[[PopMatters]]'' calling Puss a \"spry, well-dressed\" cat.<ref name=PopMatters/> ''[[Comic Book Resources]]'' writer Rob Levin described him as \"a legend in his own right\", with an \"upright strut and leather boots\".<ref name=ComicBookResources/> [[Christy Lemire]] of ''[[Boston.com]]'' said that Puss \"looks so soft and fluffy and tactile in his little, leather boots, his ... feathered hat and his shiny sword\";<ref name=Boston.com>{{cite web|url=http://archive.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2011/10/24/review_puss_in_boots_a_lively_spin_off/|title=Review: 'Puss in Boots' a lively spin-off|date=October 24, 2011|last=Lemire|first=Christy|website=[[Boston.com]]|access-date=June 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610223837/http://archive.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2011/10/24/review_puss_in_boots_a_lively_spin_off/|archive-date=June 10, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Christy Lemire}}</ref> she described him as \"a tabby cat decked out in tiny Zorro duds\".<ref name=Today.com>{{cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/shrek-2-rare-sequel-succeeds-wbna4999152|title='Shrek 2' is the rare sequel that succeeds|date=May 17, 2004|last=Lemire|first=Christy|website=[[Today (American TV program)|Today]]|access-date=June 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610171838/https://www.today.com/popculture/shrek-2-rare-sequel-succeeds-wbna4999152|archive-date=June 10, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Christy Lemire}}</ref> Todd McCarthy called Puss \"a short orange critter with green eyes, feathered hat and large boots\",<ref name=TheHollywoodReporter2/> and [[A. O. Scott]] of ''The New York Times'' praised his \"convincingly animated fur\".<ref name=TheNewYorkTimes3/> Puss's hat has been described as \"jaunty\",<ref name=Boston.com/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whatsontv.co.uk/news/film-review-puss-in-boots-antonios-pussy-galore-takes-centre-stage-322510/|title=Film review \u2013 Puss in Boots \u2013 Antonio's pussy galore takes centre stage|last=Best|first=Jason|magazine=[[What's on TV]]|access-date=September 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901002432/https://www.whatsontv.co.uk/news/film-review-puss-in-boots-antonios-pussy-galore-takes-centre-stage-322510/|archive-date=September 1, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and as a \"[[Charles de Batz de Castelmore d'Artagnan|d'Artagnan]] hat\".<ref name=TheTelegraph2/> Graham Young of the ''[[Birmingham Post]]'' stated that ''Puss in Boots'' was \"one of the most entertaining animations\" he had ever seen, citing Puss's \"wondrous\", \"little teeth\" as a contributing factor to this.<ref name=BirminghamPost>{{cite web|url=https://www.birminghampost.co.uk/whats-on/film-tv/movie-reviews-puss-boots-new-3915774|title=Movie Reviews: Puss In Boots, New Year's Eve, The Deep Blue Sea, The Big Year, The Thing, The British Guide To Showing Off|date=December 7, 2011|last1=Young|first1=Graham|last2=Laws|first2=Roz|newspaper=[[Birmingham Post]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630145157/https://www.birminghampost.co.uk/whats-on/film-tv/movie-reviews-puss-boots-new-3915774|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The character has been regarded as \"tiny\",<ref name=AnimationWorldNetwork2/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/antonio-banderas-on-playing-pablo-picasso-genius/|title=Antonio Banderas on playing Pablo Picasso|date=April 8, 2018|last=Bufano|first=Mikaela|website=[[CBS News]]|access-date=November 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112163203/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/antonio-banderas-on-playing-pablo-picasso-genius/|archive-date=November 12, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> with a ''[[Spin South West]]'' writer calling him \"small in stature, but huge in personality\".<ref name=SpinSouthWest/>\n\n[[File:Puss_in_Boots_Widening_His_Eyes.png|thumb|left|Puss in Boots's ability to widen his eyes to trick his enemies ''(pictured above)'' has been praised by critics.<ref name=IGN/><ref name=PopMatters/><ref name=TheNational/>|alt=Screenshot of a helpless-looking Puss in Boots, with big eyes]]\nPuss's ability to trick his opponents with his eyes has also been praised, with ''[[NJ.com]]'' writer Mark Voger describing it as Puss's \"sympathy-winning big-eyes technique\".<ref name=NJ>{{cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2012/02/tower_heist_yakuza_weapon_puss.html|title='Tower Heist,' 'Yakuza Weapon,' 'Puss in Boots' DVD reviews|date=February 24, 2012|last=Voger|first=Mark|website=[[NJ.com]]|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706113703/https://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2012/02/tower_heist_yakuza_weapon_puss.html|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Katharine M. Rogers wrote in her book titled ''Cat'' that while Puss is \"an ostentatiously fierce swashbuckler\", he is also able to \"instantly melt any opponent by gazing at him\", using his \"steady, confiding gaze\";<ref name=Book1/> she thought that Puss's eyes \"seem to consist entirely of warmly dark, liquid pupils\".<ref name=Book1/> James Mottram of ''[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]'' viewed the way Puss was \"widening his eyes and mewing\" as his \"main weapon\", referring to it as \"a comic gem that, wisely, the filmmakers only resort to once\" (in ''Puss in Boots'') and feeling this is a detail that makes the film a delight.<ref name=TheNational/> Ben Sherlock of ''[[Screen Rant]]'' regarded Puss as \"popular\" and said that \"his technique of looking adorable with gigantic eyes to get his opponents to drop their guard before launching an attack on them\" never fails.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/shrek-funniest-quotes/|title=Shrek's 10 Funniest Quotes|date=June 7, 2019|last=Sherlock|first=Ben|website=[[Screen Rant]]|access-date=November 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112125748/https://screenrant.com/shrek-funniest-quotes/|archive-date=November 12, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Jesse Hassenger described Puss as a \"swashbuckling cat with the trappings of an actual feline, like purring and looking adorable to disarm enemies\".<ref name=PopMatters/> Hassenger called Puss's eyes \"big\", \"cute\", and \"not always easy to resist\" (despite their purpose being \"visible\").<ref name=PopMatters/> Graham Young described Puss's eyes as \"emerald mince pies\".<ref name=BirminghamPost/> ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s Dan Jolin called the character's \"dilated-pupils\" a \"cute act\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/shrek-third/review/|title=Shrek The Third Review|date=May 23, 2007|last=Jolin|first=Dan|magazine=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704002513/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/shrek-third/review/|archive-date=July 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and another ''Empire'' writer also praised Puss's ability to widen his eyes.<ref name=Empire2/> Nev Pierce of the ''[[BBC]]'' described his eyes as \"cutesy\" and \"saucer-like\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/06/24/shrek_2_2004_review.shtml|title=Shrek 2 (2004)|date=July 1, 2004|last=Pierce|first=Nev|website=[[BBC]]|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706084138/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/06/24/shrek_2_2004_review.shtml|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''IGN'' writer Jeff Otto wrote that Puss \"can give the most adorable wide-eyed look\" to \"lure\" his enemies into \"his vicious swashbuckling attacks\".<ref name=IGN/> Christy Lemire praised that Puss is \"working those big, green eyes for maximum manipulative effect\".<ref name=Boston.com/> Puss's \"big eyes\" were also described as a [[running gag]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.com/news/2010/may/28/emshrek-forever-afterem/|title=Shrek Forever After|date=May 28, 2010|last=Palladino|first=D. J.|newspaper=[[Santa Barbara Independent]]|access-date=September 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921161009/https://www.independent.com/news/2010/may/28/emshrek-forever-afterem/|archive-date=September 21, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nReviewers have provided comments regarding the character's popularity. Steven Lebowitz of ''[[AXS (company)|AXS]]'' said that Puss was \"just as popular as Shrek\",<ref name=AXS/> and Joseph Airdo of the same website called him \"arguably the most popular\" character in the ''Shrek'' franchise.<ref name=AXS2>{{cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/news/movie-review-puss-in-boots-97147|title=Movie Review: Puss in Boots|date=October 30, 2011|last=Airdo|first=Joseph|website=[[AXS (company)|AXS]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630144632/https://www.axs.com/news/movie-review-puss-in-boots-97147|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Ashley Rodriguez of ''[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]'' also described Puss as a \"popular ''Shrek'' character\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1009772/netflix-nflx-is-trying-to-make-tv-into-a-more-active-experience-and-its-starting-with-kids-shows/|title=Netflix is trying to make TV a more active experience\u2014starting with kids shows|date=June 20, 2017|last=Rodriguez|first=Ashley|website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]|access-date=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730153833/https://qz.com/1009772/netflix-nflx-is-trying-to-make-tv-into-a-more-active-experience-and-its-starting-with-kids-shows/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''Tech Times'' writer [[Robin Parrish]] called Puss \"everyone's favorite ''Shrek'' sidekick\".<ref name=TechTimes/> Christina Radish characterized Puss as an \"adorable little creature\" who had become \"a fan favorite in the ''Shrek'' films\",<ref name=Collider2/> and ''[[Quickflix]]''{{'}}s Simon Miraudo called him one of the franchise's \"signature characters\".<ref name=Quickflix/> Rob Carnevale stated that Puss was \"the real star of the franchise\" to many ''Shrek'' fans.<ref name=IndieLondon3/> Andrew Penn Romine said that he is \"one of the most popular characters in recent animation history\".<ref name=FantasyMagazine/> Marc Savlov of ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]'' felt that Puss was \"the freshest and sharpest ... surprise\" of ''Shrek 2'';<ref name=TheAustinChronicle/> he was described as this \"film's most delightful new character\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,638431,00.html|title=The Honeymoon Is Ogre|date=May 16, 2004|last=Schickel|first=Richard|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=June 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610224113/http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,638431,00.html|archive-date=June 10, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Richard Schickel}}</ref> \"the most hilarious new character\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/shrek-2-189216/|title=Shrek 2|date=May 19, 2004|last=Travers|first=Peter|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=June 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610224234/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/shrek-2-189216/|archive-date=June 10, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Peter Travers}}</ref> the \"most memorable character\",<ref name=IGN/> \"the most fantastic addition of all\",<ref name=Today.com/> \"the franchise's greatest character\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/best-family-movies/|title=The 30 best family movies to watch with the kids, from Disney classics to Studio Ghibli masterpieces|date=August 6, 2019|last=Einarsson|first=Erlingur|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|access-date=August 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817130635/https://www.gamesradar.com/best-family-movies/|archive-date=August 17, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and \"the best character of all\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2004/05/19/shrek2/|title=\"Shrek 2\"|date=May 20, 2004|last=Zacharek|first=Stephanie|website=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|access-date=June 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610224543/https://www.salon.com/2004/05/19/shrek2/|archive-date=June 10, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Stephanie Zacharek}}</ref> Stephen Holden wrote that although Puss \"has his charms\", \"he is not as memorable a character as Shrek or Shrek's mouthy sidekick, Donkey\",<ref name=TheNewYorkTimes4/> and Matt Fowler of ''IGN'' described him as \"perhaps better suited as a side character\".<ref name=IGN2>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/10/24/puss-in-boots-review|title=Puss in Boots Review|date=October 24, 2011|last=Fowler|first=Matt|website=[[IGN]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630144147/http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/10/24/puss-in-boots-review|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Puss was ranked 11th on ''Empire''{{'}}s top 50 animated film characters list.<ref name=Empire2/>\n\nCritics have praised Banderas's voicing. Rob Levin said that Puss has \"a decidedly Latin flavor\" in the ''Shrek'' films because of Banderas, who \"plays the part with gusto, giving the tiny hero all the bravado and charm of his real-life persona\".<ref name=ComicBookResources/> According to Andrew Penn Romine, Banderas voiced Puss \"with feline gravitas\".<ref name=FantasyMagazine/> Rob Carnevale called Banderas's performance \"inimitable\".<ref name=IndieLondon3/> ''[[Rogue Pictures|IAmRogue]]''{{'}}s Dana Gardner wrote that Banderas \"brought plenty of comedy to the role of Puss by playing the character so melodramatically\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iamrogue.com/news/interviews/item/5882-chris-miller-talks-puss-in-boots-on-blu-ray-and-dvd.html|title=IAR Exclusive Interview: Chirs Miller Talks 'Puss in Boots' on Blu-Ray and DVD|date=February 21, 2012|last=Gardner|first=Dana|website=[[Rogue Pictures|IAmRogue]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630143724/http://www.iamrogue.com/news/interviews/item/5882-chris-miller-talks-puss-in-boots-on-blu-ray-and-dvd.html|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Matt Fowler found Banderas \"perfectly suitable as Puss\",<ref name=IGN2/> and Todd McCarthy called his performance \"spirited and knowing\".<ref name=TheHollywoodReporter2/> James Mottram praised \"Banderas's charm\" as well.<ref name=TheNational/> Graham Young felt that Banderas's performance improved ''Shrek 2'', resembling his acting in ''The Mask of Zorro'',<ref name=BirminghamPost/> and Chrissy Iley described Puss as \"a feline spoof of [Banderas's] Zorro character\".<ref name=TheTelegraph/> Donna Bowater of ''The Telegraph'' called Banderas's performance \"famous\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/film-news/8914277/Salma-Hayek-Antonio-Banderas-is-crazy.html|title=Salma Hayek: Antonio Banderas is 'crazy'|date=November 24, 2011|last=Bowater|first=Donna|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630145510/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/film-news/8914277/Salma-Hayek-Antonio-Banderas-is-crazy.html|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Jeff Otto said that Banderas \"lends a fantastic energy to the character\", making viewers \"wish for more of him\".<ref name=IGN/> [[Alan Jones (film critic)|Alan Jones]] of ''[[Radio Times]]'' also enjoyed Banderas's voice acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/film/crnk7/shrek-2/|title=Shrek 2|last=Jones|first=Alan|magazine=[[Radio Times]]|access-date=September 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926220701/https://www.radiotimes.com/film/crnk7/shrek-2/|archive-date=September 26, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Alan Jones (film critic)}}</ref> According to an ''Empire'' reviewer, Puss was \"voiced to perfection by Banderas\".<ref name=Empire2/> In the book titled ''Stars in World Cinema: Screen Icons and Star Systems Across Cultures'', the authors wrote that the \"European roots\" of the fairy tale \"Puss in Boots\" were \"revived through the presence of Banderas\".<ref name=Book2>{{cite book|title=Stars in World Cinema: Screen Icons and Star Systems Across Cultures|last1=Bandhauer|first1=Andrea|last2=Royer|first2=Michelle|pages=97\u201398|isbn=978-1-78076-977-6|publisher=[[I.B. Tauris]]|year=2015}}</ref> They stated that while Banderas's \"on-screen persona\" had been based on \"his sensuality and body image\", he then exchanged this representation for the image of \"an animated ginger cat\".<ref name=Book2/> The writers also commented that Puss's voice \"was intended to speak to the audience's [internalized] views regarding accent and regional profile\";<ref name=Book2/> they said it was \"vital\" for Puss \"not to belong to the dominant cultural group\" despite being \"adopted into that group\".<ref name=Book2/> In his book titled ''The Animated Movie Guide'', author [[Jerry Beck]] wrote that Banderas voiced Puss with \"a Castilian accent\" in the Latin American version and with \"an Andalusian accent\" in the Spanish version;<ref name=Book3>{{cite book|title=The Animated Movie Guide|last=Beck|first=Jerry|page=[https://archive.org/details/animatedmoviegui0000beck/page/250 250]|isbn=978-1-55652-591-9|publisher=[[Chicago Review Press]]|year=2005|author-link=Jerry Beck|url=https://archive.org/details/animatedmoviegui0000beck/page/250}}</ref> he mentioned that both accents sounded \"funny\" to their respective [[target audience]]s.<ref name=Book3/> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s Maureen Lee Lenker said that Puss had become a \"fan favorite\" after his first appearance in the ''Shrek'' franchise, mostly because of Banderas's \"smooth Spanish accent\";<ref name=EntertainmentWeekly/> the \"tie-in\" with Banderas was stated to \"largely\" contribute to Puss's popularity.<ref name=AnimationWorldNetwork/>\n\n===Merchandise===\nMerchandise based on the character has been released, including [[plush toy]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2011/10/puss-in-boots-imax-photo-upload-contest/|title=Puss in Boots IMAX Photo Upload Contest|date=October 25, 2011|last=Venables|first=Michael|magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|access-date=August 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828143950/https://www.wired.com/2011/10/puss-in-boots-imax-photo-upload-contest/|archive-date=August 28, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The company [[Funko]] has launched vinyl figures depicting Puss.<ref name=ScreenRant>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/shrek-gift-guide/|title=10 Perfect Gifts For The Shrek Fan In Your Life|date=May 20, 2019|last=Olivieri|first=Joshua|website=[[Screen Rant]]|access-date=May 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526222340/https://screenrant.com/shrek-gift-guide/|archive-date=May 26, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sciencefiction.com/2015/02/16/toy-fair-2015-funko-pop-vinyl-reveals/|title=Toy Fair 2015: Funko POP! Vinyl Reveals|date=February 16, 2015|last=Desjardins|first=Jordan|website=ScienceFiction.com|access-date=August 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828134656/http://sciencefiction.com/2015/02/16/toy-fair-2015-funko-pop-vinyl-reveals/|archive-date=August 28, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[McDonald's]] toys inspired by Puss have also been produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mcdonalds/mcdonalds-happy-meals-get-apples-fewer-fries-idUSTRE76P41I20110726|title=McDonald's Happy Meals get apples, fewer fries|date=July 26, 2011|last=Baertlein|first=Lisa|website=[[Reuters]]|access-date=July 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828114153/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mcdonalds/mcdonalds-happy-meals-get-apples-fewer-fries-idUSTRE76P41I20110726|archive-date=August 28, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brandchannel.com/2011/10/28/at-the-movies-did-rum-diarys-nothing-in-moderation-motto-scare-away-brand-partners/|title=At the Movies: Did Rum Diary's \"Nothing in Moderation\" Motto Scare Away Brand Partners?|date=October 28, 2011|last=Sauer|first=Abe|website=[[Brandchannel]]|access-date=August 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829192509/https://www.brandchannel.com/2011/10/28/at-the-movies-did-rum-diarys-nothing-in-moderation-motto-scare-away-brand-partners/|archive-date=August 29, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Pez candy dispenser]]s based on Puss have been created as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://us.pez.com/products/shrek|title=Shrek|website=[[Pez|PEZ.com]]|access-date=August 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823233235/https://us.pez.com/products/shrek|archive-date=August 23, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Backpack]]s that portray Puss on their print have been released, and articles of clothing inspired by him have also been produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2011/12/19/win-four-tickets-to-see-shrek-the-musical-plus-puss-in-boots-goodies_n_7382874.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer_us=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xILnJvLw&guce_referrer_cs=basw_nsZLEyEnByEx8wqxw|title=Win Four Tickets To See Shrek The Musical Plus Puss in Boots Goodies!|date=December 19, 2011|last=Stansfield|first=Liz|website=[[HuffPost UK]]|access-date=August 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828151625/https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2011/12/19/win-four-tickets-to-see-shrek-the-musical-plus-puss-in-boots-goodies_n_7382874.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer_us=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xILnJvLw&guce_referrer_cs=basw_nsZLEyEnByEx8wqxw|archive-date=August 28, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A [[Monopoly (game)|''Monopoly'']] game based on Puss and other ''Shrek'' characters has been invented.<ref name=ScreenRant/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Shrek}}\n{{Puss in Boots}}\n\n[[Category:Shrek characters]]\n[[Category:Anthropomorphic cats]]<!-- Subcategory of [[Category:Anthropomorphic animal characters]] -->\n[[Category:Fictional cats]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who became a protagonist in a spin-off]]\n[[Category:Fictional swordsmen]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 2004]]<!-- Subcategory of [[Category:Fictional characters introduced in 2004]] -->\n[[Category:Film sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Male characters in animation]]\n[[Category:Male characters in film]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Short description|Character in the Shrek franchise}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Puss in Boots (''Shrek'')}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color            = #FFA500\n| name             = Puss in Boots\n| series           = [[Shrek (franchise)|Shrek]]\n| image            = Puss_in_Boots_from_Shrek.png\n| alt              = A fictional cat from the ''Shrek'' franchise wearing boots, a feathered hat, and a cape while wielding a sword\n| caption          = Puss in Boots as he appears in the<br />''Shrek'' franchise\n| first            = ''[[Shrek 2]]'' (2004)\n| last             = ''[[The Adventures of Puss in Boots]]'' (2018)\n| voice            = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Antonio Banderas]]<br />({{small|''Shrek 2''}}, {{small|''[[Shrek the Third]]''}}, {{small|''[[Shrek Forever After]]''}}, {{small|''[[Puss in Boots (2011 film)|Puss in Boots]]''}})\n*[[Eric Bauza]]<br />({{small|''The Adventures of Puss in Boots''}})\n*[[Andr\u00e9 Sogliuzzo]]<br />({{small|[[Shrek video games|''Shrek'' video games]]}})\n*[[Frank Welker]]<br />({{small|[[meow]]ing [[sound effect]]s}})\n}}\n| lbl1             = Inspired by\n| data1            = [[Puss in Boots]]\n| aliases          = {{Plainlist|\n*Diablo Gato\n*The Furry Lover\n*Chupacabra\n*Frisky Two Times\n*The Ginger Hit Man\n}}\n| species          = [[Cat]]\n| gender           = Male\n| weapon           = Sword\n| family           = [[List of Shrek characters#Imelda|Imelda]] (adoptive mother)\n| origin           = San Ricardo\n}}\n'''Puss in Boots''' is a [[main character]] in the [[Shrek (franchise)|''Shrek'' franchise]] and the [[title character]] (and protagonist) of the film ''[[Puss in Boots (2011 film)|Puss in Boots]]'' (2011). He made his first appearance in the film ''[[Shrek 2]]'' (2004), soon becoming [[Shrek (character)|Shrek]]'s partner and helper (alongside [[Donkey (Shrek)|Donkey]]). In the film ''[[Shrek the Third]]'' (2007), Puss helps Shrek find the heir to the throne of the Far Far Away Kingdom. The film ''[[Shrek Forever After]]'' (2010) is primarily set in an [[Parallel universes in fiction|alternate universe]], where Puss is [[Princess Fiona]]'s [[pet]] and has gained weight after his retirement. In the [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] and [[prequel]] ''Puss in Boots'', his origins are described. Puss also appears in the [[Netflix]] television series centered on him, ''[[The Adventures of Puss in Boots]]''.\n\nPuss was inspired by the title [[Character (arts)|character]] of the [[fairy tale]] \"[[Puss in Boots]]\". His design, created by Tom Hester, was based on real [[cats]]. Several characters were used as inspirations for Puss's characterization, such as [[Zorro]] and [[Indiana Jones]]. The idea of Puss as the protagonist of a film was explored after his debut appearance. [[Antonio Banderas]] voices Puss in the English, Spanish, and Italian [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubs]] of the ''Shrek'' franchise. While he initially tried a high-pitched voice for the character, he and the ''Shrek 2'' filmmakers decided on a tone that was deeper than his normal voice. Banderas said that voicing Puss was an important part of his career. [[Eric Bauza]] provides Puss's voice in ''The Adventures of Puss in Boots''.\n\nThe character has received generally positive reviews, with critics praising his depiction and considering him a source of [[comic relief]]. Reviewers have regarded Puss as a popular ''Shrek'' character. Banderas's [[voice acting]] has also been praised. Merchandise inspired by the character has been produced.\n\n==Development==\n==={{anchor|Conception and creation}}Concept and creation===\nPuss in Boots is inspired by the [[title character]] of the [[Puss in Boots|fairy tale]] with the same name.<ref name=ComicBookResources>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/director-chris-miller-ventures-into-surreal-world-of-puss-in-boots/|title=Director Chris Miller Ventures Into 'Surreal' World of Puss in Boots|date=October 28, 2011|last=Levin|first=Rob|website=[[Comic Book Resources]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703231847/https://www.cbr.com/director-chris-miller-ventures-into-surreal-world-of-puss-in-boots/|archive-date=July 3, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Character (arts)|Character]] designer Tom Hester provided Puss's design, which was based on [[cat]]s owned by ''[[Shrek]]'' [[Film director|director]] [[Andrew Adamson]] and effects supervisor Ken Bielenberg. After [[Antonio Banderas]] had been cast as Puss's voice, the ''Shrek'' [[animator]]s analyzed his performance as the title character in ''[[The Mask of Zorro]]'' (1998) for insight into Puss's depiction.<ref name=AnimationWorldNetwork>{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/book-review-art-puss-boots|title=Book Review: 'The Art of Puss In Boots'|date=February 14, 2012|last=Patten|first=Fred|website=[[Animation World Network]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630130341/https://www.awn.com/animationworld/book-review-art-puss-boots|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Fred Patten}}</ref> Inspired by Banderas's [[Zorro]], the [[Filmmaking|filmmakers]] decided to make Puss's origins Spanish (instead of the [[fairy tale]]'s French).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flayrah.com/3716/review-art-puss-boots-ramin-zahed|title=Review: 'The Art of Puss in Boots', by Ramin Zahed|date=October 22, 2011|last=Patten|first=Fred|website=Flayrah|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630130712/http://www.flayrah.com/3716/review-art-puss-boots-ramin-zahed|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Fred Patten}}</ref> When [[Computer animation|computer-animating]] Puss, new animation tools were required for his fur, belt, and the plume on his hat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/vfxworld/decade-shrek-tech|title=A Decade of 'Shrek' Tech|date=May 20, 2010|last=Desowitz|first=Bill|website=[[Animation World Network]]|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704111547/https://www.awn.com/vfxworld/decade-shrek-tech|archive-date=July 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Chris Miller (animator)|Chris Miller]], head of story of the film ''[[Shrek 2]]'' (2004),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/shrek-pair-directed-showest-fete-131348|title='Shrek' pair directed to ShoWest fete|date=March 6, 2007|last=Kilday|first=Gregg|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=July 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731103821/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/shrek-pair-directed-showest-fete-131348|archive-date=July 31, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://animatedviews.com/2007/miller-hui-on-shrek-3/|title=Directors Miller and Hui on Shrek the Third|date=May 21, 2007|last=Armstrong|first=Josh|website=Animated Views|access-date=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730204734/http://animatedviews.com/2007/miller-hui-on-shrek-3/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/shrek-the-third/4032264.article|title=Shrek The Third|date=May 10, 2007|last=Hazelton|first=John|website=[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]|access-date=July 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731104442/https://www.screendaily.com/shrek-the-third/4032264.article|archive-date=July 31, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> said that he enjoyed the character of Puss as much as viewers seemed to; he and everyone else involved in ''Shrek 2'' wanted to add more scenes related to Puss to the film. Miller described Puss as \"a really cool, dynamic [[sidekick]] character at that time\", saying that the filmmakers had decided to link the character to a \"weird history\" in which he had been \"everywhere\" and done \"everything\".<ref name=Collider>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/chris-miller-puss-in-boots-interview/|title=Director Chris Miller Talks Puss in Boots and Collaborating With Guillermo del Toro|date=October 27, 2011|last=Radish|first=Christina|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630132400/http://collider.com/chris-miller-puss-in-boots-interview/|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He and the other filmmakers wondered what the story of Puss would look like and why he had his accent. According to Miller, writing and developing Puss had been \"so much fun\", and the character had a \"huge impact\" in ''Shrek 2'' by stealing so many scenes.<ref name=Collider/> Miller said that he had \"always loved\" the character and had been \"fascinated by where Puss had been before\".<ref name=FantasyMagazine>{{cite web|url=http://www.fantasy-magazine.com/new/new-nonfiction/feature-interview-puss-in-boots-director-chris-miller/|title=Feature Interview: Puss in Boots Director Chris Miller|last=Romine|first=Andrew Penn|magazine=[[Fantasy Magazine]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630132553/http://www.fantasy-magazine.com/new/new-nonfiction/feature-interview-puss-in-boots-director-chris-miller/|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Puss repeatedly mentions \"some great adventure\" (without details) in the ''Shrek'' films, and Miller wanted to know more about his origins (such as where his boots came from).<ref name=FantasyMagazine/> Miller called Puss his favorite ''Shrek'' character,<ref name=TheFilmExperience>{{cite web|url=http://thefilmexperience.net/blog/2012/2/15/interview-the-man-behind-puss-in-boots-is-a-dog-person.html|title=Interview: The Man Behind \"Puss in Boots\" Is A Dog Person!|date=February 15, 2012|website=The Film Experience|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630133731/http://thefilmexperience.net/blog/2012/2/15/interview-the-man-behind-puss-in-boots-is-a-dog-person.html|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> who had \"always stood out\",<ref name=FantasyMagazine/> and could not imagine anyone other than Banderas [[Voice acting|voicing]] him;<ref name=Quickflix>{{cite web|url=https://www.quickflix.com.au/News/Interviews/PussinBoots/8297|title=Interview \u2013 Chris Miller, Puss in Boots|date=December 7, 2011|last=Miraudo|first=Simon|website=[[Quickflix]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630133341/https://www.quickflix.com.au/News/Interviews/PussinBoots/8297|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> soon after the character had been created, Banderas was offered the role. Miller commented that the actor's performance was \"pretty brilliant\".<ref name=Quickflix/>\n\nAfter realizing at the 2004 [[Cannes Film Festival]] how much viewers enjoyed Puss's character, [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]], co-founder of [[DreamWorks Animation]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/aug/07/itv-joins-hollywood-giants-to-back-video-streaming-service-for-mobiles|title=ITV joins Hollywood giants to back video streaming service for mobiles|date=August 7, 2018|last=Sweney|first=Mark|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=September 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904001334/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/aug/07/itv-joins-hollywood-giants-to-back-video-streaming-service-for-mobiles|archive-date=September 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> began considering \"the idea of possibly continuing with the character in the ''Shrek'' series\" and creating a film with Puss as the [[protagonist]].<ref name=Collider2>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/antonio-banderas-salma-hayek-puss-in-boots-interview/|title=Antonio Banderas and Salma Hayek Puss in Boots Interview|date=October 28, 2011|last=Radish|first=Christina|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630131029/http://collider.com/antonio-banderas-salma-hayek-puss-in-boots-interview/|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Katzenberg called Puss a \"[[scene stealer]]\" and said he \"seemed to beg for his own film\" after his first appearance in the [[Shrek (franchise)|''Shrek'' franchise]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/jeffrey-katzenberg/241771/jeffrey-katzenberg-interview-penguins-dreamworks-universes|title=Jeffrey Katzenberg interview: Penguins, DreamWorks, universes|date=December 2, 2014|last=Brew|first=Simon|website=[[Den of Geek]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630131345/http://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/jeffrey-katzenberg/241771/jeffrey-katzenberg-interview-penguins-dreamworks-universes|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Miller, who also directed the film ''[[Puss in Boots (2011 film)|Puss in Boots]]'' (2011),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://animatedviews.com/2012/chris-miller-discusses-his-oscar-nom-and-puss-in-boots/|title=Chris Miller discusses his Oscar nom and Puss in Boots|date=February 22, 2012|last=Sollie|first=Jeremy|website=Animated Views|access-date=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730205334/http://animatedviews.com/2012/chris-miller-discusses-his-oscar-nom-and-puss-in-boots/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/puss-boots-chris-miller-madagascar-conrad-vernon-295084|title='Puss in Boots' Director Chris Miller to Appear in 'Madagascar 3'|date=February 26, 2012|last=Giardina|first=Carolyn|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730210051/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/puss-boots-chris-miller-madagascar-conrad-vernon-295084|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=AnimationMagazine/> knew that Puss was suitable for a [[standalone film]],<ref name=TheFilmExperience/> and he was pleased when Banderas quickly accepted the role.<ref name=Tribute>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribute.ca/interviews/chris-miller-puss-in-boots/director/25039/|title=Chris Miller (Puss in Boots) Interview 2011|magazine=[[Tribute (magazine)|Tribute]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630132022/https://www.tribute.ca/interviews/chris-miller-puss-in-boots/director/25039/|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Miller was happy with DreamWorks's decision to create a film about Puss and excited to contribute to its production.<ref name=Collider/> He said the idea of Puss having his own film had been considered since the character had joined the ''Shrek'' franchise, attributing this to \"the size and scope of that character\" and \"the personality that Antonio infused that character with\".<ref name=IndieLondon>{{cite web|url=http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Film-Review/puss-in-boots-chris-miller-interview|title=Puss in Boots \u2013 Chris Miller interview|last=Carnevale|first=Rob|website=IndieLondon|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630134234/http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Film-Review/puss-in-boots-chris-miller-interview|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Although the filmmakers initially wanted to bring cats to the DreamWorks studios to study them for the development of Puss, the DreamWorks staff suggested watching [[YouTube]] cat videos instead. According to Miller, YouTube was the filmmakers' \"great resource\" of inspiration to which they added their \"personal experience\".<ref name=ComicBookResources/> He said that cats, \"as seriously as they take themselves\", \"can never resist their true nature\", and he cited Puss's \"hissing\" as an example.<ref name=ComicBookResources/>\n\nThe ''Puss in Boots'' filmmakers knew from the beginning that something about the character \"demanded [the story] just be larger than life\".<ref name=Quickflix/> While the story had initially been conceptualized as \"loosely based\" on the classic fairy tale, involving \"Puss and three sons of the [[Puss in Boots#Plot|miller]]\", the filmmakers decided to create \"a new story told on a grander scale\", \"something that would be more worthy of\" Puss.<ref name=AnimationMagazine>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/features/a-swashbuckling-cat-for-all-seasons/|title=A Swashbuckling Cat for All Seasons|date=October 7, 2011|last=Zahed|first=Ramin|magazine=[[Animation Magazine]]|access-date=September 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907141801/http://www.animationmagazine.net/features/a-swashbuckling-cat-for-all-seasons/|archive-date=September 7, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"[[Spaghetti Western]] style and structure\" also inspired Puss's character,<ref name=FantasyMagazine/> and the filmmakers decided to use \"big screen legends\" as inspiration.<ref name=FantasyMagazine/> Miller cited [[Clint Eastwood]] as one of the \"classic cinematic figures\" inspiring Puss's portrayal and regarded him as \"a strong force\" since there was \"something about Clint that was in the cat\".<ref name=Quickflix/> He also cited [[Indiana Jones]]'s \"adventurous spirit\", [[James Bond (literary character)|James Bond]] and [[Errol Flynn]].<ref name=Quickflix/> Miller also cited Zorro as an inspiration for Puss since Banderas (who played Zorro) voiced him,<ref name=Quickflix/> and he said that \"Antonio's persona [had] really dictated so many of the choices that [had been] made\" about Puss's character in ''Puss in Boots''.<ref name=ComicBookResources/> According to Miller, it is \"very difficult to tell the difference\" between Puss and Banderas.<ref name=TheTelegraph>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/8928127/Antonio-Banderas-on-Puss-In-Boots.html|title=Antonio Banderas on Puss in Boots|date=December 4, 2011|last=Iley|first=Chrissy|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630134551/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/8928127/Antonio-Banderas-on-Puss-In-Boots.html|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe filmmakers decided to give Puss \"a heavy story\" in ''Puss in Boots'';<ref name=Collider/> they felt that breaking his heart would be \"really important\", and they wanted to offer him \"something to redeem himself from and clear his name\".<ref name=Collider/> They debated whether Puss would be portrayed as a misunderstood fugitive. Miller said that although Puss could have been depicted as deceptive, the filmmakers had decided to portray him as blameworthy; robbing the bank was not Puss's plan and he ran away \"out of fear\", but he had to take responsibility for his actions.<ref name=Collider/> Miller stated that Puss's \"desire to believe the best in someone else\" and to \"hang on to a friendship\" represent \"the kind of things that get him in trouble\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2011/03/29/puss-in-boots-humpty-dumpty/|title='Puss in Boots': Cat has egg in his face in 'Shrek' spin-off|date=March 29, 2011|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=June 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606224152/https://ew.com/article/2011/03/29/puss-in-boots-humpty-dumpty/|archive-date=June 6, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Anthony Breznican}}</ref> Puss's backstory was meant to indicate the \"heaviness on his mind and in his heart\", and why he was on the run despite his \"cool life\".<ref name=Collider/> Miller said that Puss was a \"pretty wide open\" character when it came to his portrayal in the film;<ref name=FantasyMagazine/> Puss adds a dramatic note to everything, which the filmmakers used \"to attach a very tragic story to his life\".<ref name=FantasyMagazine/> Miller stated that \"the heavy dramatic themes\" fit Puss's character well, making the character's journey a \"story of redemption\" in which \"he sort of walks a dark path with a hole punched in his heart\" and wishes \"to clear away the sins of his past\" and \"reclaim what was his\".<ref name=FantasyMagazine/> Miller said that Puss in his cape affirmed \"an urban legend\";<ref name=ComicBookResources/> although he wore it in marketing material, he rarely did so in the films. According to Miller, Puss's cape was \"so expensive to keep strapped to that cat\" and \"so cumbersome\" that the ''Puss in Boots'' filmmakers decided to have the character wear it for a short time, as in ''Shrek 2''.<ref name=ComicBookResources/> Miller felt that Puss's \"giant big eyes\" would appeal to viewers.<ref name=IndieLondon/> ''Puss in Boots'' [[executive producer]] [[Guillermo del Toro]] said that Puss would be taken \"to a completely different land which is very exotic\" in the future [[adventure film]] ''[[Puss in Boots 2: Nine Lives & 40 Thieves|Puss in Boots 2]]'', since Miller wanted the film to be set in a visually-different universe than ''Shrek''{{'}}s.<ref name=Collider3>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/puss-in-boots-2-news-antonio-banderas/|title=Antonio Banderas Says He Just Started Work on Puss in Boots 2|date=April 16, 2014|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630135222/http://collider.com/puss-in-boots-2-news-antonio-banderas/|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Doug Langdale]], executive producer of the television series ''[[The Adventures of Puss in Boots]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/12/the-adventures-of-puss-in-boots-season-4-exclusive-clip-shrek-netflix-1201758386/|title='The Adventures of Puss in Boots' Season 4 Exclusive Clip: Puss Shows Off His Many Powers|date=December 14, 2016|last=Murthi|first=Vikram|website=[[IndieWire]]|access-date=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730193413/https://www.indiewire.com/2016/12/the-adventures-of-puss-in-boots-season-4-exclusive-clip-shrek-netflix-1201758386/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/netflix-launches-chooseyourownadventurestyle-interactive-shows-for-kids-20170621-gwv6tz.html|title=Netflix launches choose-your-own-adventure-style interactive shows for kids|date=June 21, 2017|last=Turner|first=Adam|newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=August 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831212753/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/netflix-launches-chooseyourownadventurestyle-interactive-shows-for-kids-20170621-gwv6tz.html|archive-date=August 31, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://studybreaks.com/culture/interactive-tv-shows-next-big-tv-trend/|title=Are Interactive Shows The Next Big Trend in TV?|date=August 15, 2017|last=Litvin|first=Cherie|magazine=[[Study Breaks]]|access-date=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730201441/https://studybreaks.com/culture/interactive-tv-shows-next-big-tv-trend/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> said that in the series Puss fights \"a lot more\" compared to the films;<ref name=SpinSouthWest>{{cite web|url=http://www.spinsouthwest.com/consent.php?return=R27i4qM853pd5FTZrUpGy7xljFubRNc17VtRbIf7yV8hBqXkQIqlsqNX8emtUnNvUunByGPIAX8wpnLbx%2Bx1Ww%3D%3D|title=The Adventures of Puss in Boots now on Netflix|date=January 16, 2015|website=[[Spin South West]]|access-date=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730161448/http://www.spinsouthwest.com/consent.php?return=R27i4qM853pd5FTZrUpGy7xljFubRNc17VtRbIf7yV8hBqXkQIqlsqNX8emtUnNvUunByGPIAX8wpnLbx%2Bx1Ww%3D%3D|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> he is depicted \"more as a master swordsman with lots of extra punching, kicking and action\".<ref name=SpinSouthWest/> Langdale stated that he \"wanted to set the show earlier in Puss's life, back when he was the only one who thought he was a legend ... had more to prove, and maybe [was not] quite so awesome at everything yet\", which determined that the series would be set before the film ''Puss in Boots''.<ref name=TechTimes>{{cite web|url=https://www.techtimes.com/articles/27047/20150116/interview-netflix-puss-boots-series-creator.htm|title=Interview: Netflix's 'Puss In Boots' Series Creator On Secrets, Surprises & Why You Have To Watch|date=January 16, 2015|last=Parrish|first=Robin|website=Tech Times|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630142242/https://www.techtimes.com/articles/27047/20150116/interview-netflix-puss-boots-series-creator.htm|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Robin Parrish}}</ref> He said that since Puss is a \"hero\", the series focuses on his saving people and defeating \"bad guys\".<ref name=SpinSouthWest/> Langdale added that in the series, \"unexpected depth and nuance\" are brought to the character with comedy;<ref name=SpinSouthWest/> Puss was a \"[[nomad]]\" and a \"loner\" before the events of the series, which \"is an essential segment in Puss's life\" that taught him \"how to get along with other people\" and made him \"understand the value of friendships and relationships\".<ref name=SpinSouthWest/> According to Langdale, \"the audience [would] willingly follow\" Puss's \"charm, charisma and appeal\".<ref name=SpinSouthWest/>\n\n===Voice===\n[[File:Antonio Banderas 2014.jpg|thumb|[[Antonio Banderas]] ''(pictured above)'' voiced Puss in Boots in the English, Spanish, and Italian [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubs]] of the [[Shrek (franchise)|''Shrek'' franchise]].<ref name=AnimationWorldNetwork/><ref name=TheAtlantic/><ref name=RTE/>|alt=A smiling, alert Antonio Banderas]]\nAntonio Banderas voiced Puss in the ''Shrek'' franchise.<ref name=AnimationWorldNetwork/><ref name=TheAtlantic/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/antonio-banderas-reveals-how-his-puss-in-boots-character-follows-him-everywhere/|title=Antonio Banderas Reveals How His Puss in Boots Character Follows Him Everywhere|date=April 23, 2018|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|access-date=July 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731125722/https://people.com/tv/antonio-banderas-reveals-how-his-puss-in-boots-character-follows-him-everywhere/|archive-date=July 31, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Banderas said that his initial motivation to voice Puss was that he enjoyed the film ''Shrek'' (2001).<ref name=AXS>{{cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/news/puss-in-boots-interview-with-antonio-banderas-and-salma-hayek-100107|title='Puss in Boots' interview with Antonio Banderas and Salma Hayek|date=October 31, 2011|last=Lebowitz|first=Steven|website=[[AXS (company)|AXS]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630141040/https://www.axs.com/news/puss-in-boots-interview-with-antonio-banderas-and-salma-hayek-100107|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> According to the actor, he was chosen for the role of Puss because of his Spanish accent.<ref name=TheNewYorkTimes>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.nytimes.com/2010/05/16/movies/16shrek.html|title=He's Big, He's Green, and He's Gone|date=May 14, 2010|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630140537/https://mobile.nytimes.com/2010/05/16/movies/16shrek.html|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Dave Itzkoff}}</ref> According to Banderas, he was on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] for the musical ''[[Nine (musical)|Nine]]'' when Jeffrey Katzenberg approached him about taking the role.<ref name=ETCanada>{{cite web|url=https://etcanada.com/news/532979/antonio-banderas-talks-being-pursued-by-madonna-and-teases-new-puss-in-boots-movie/|title=Antonio Banderas Talks Being Pursued By Madonna And Teases New 'Puss In Boots' Movie|date=October 31, 2019|last=Atad|first=Corey|website=[[Entertainment Tonight Canada|ET Canada]]|access-date=November 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107163313/https://etcanada.com/news/532979/antonio-banderas-talks-being-pursued-by-madonna-and-teases-new-puss-in-boots-movie/|archive-date=November 7, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The ''Shrek 2'' filmmakers showed him \"a lot of paintings of the character\", and he realized how \"little\" Puss was.<ref name=EntertainmentWeekly>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/movies/2018/06/07/puss-in-boots-different-voice-antonio-banderas/|title=Antonio Banderas on how Shrek's Puss in Boots almost sounded different|date=June 7, 2018|last=Lenker|first=Maureen Lee|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=July 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731110059/http://ew.com/movies/2018/06/07/puss-in-boots-different-voice-antonio-banderas/|archive-date=July 31, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Banderas said that he had developed a strategy for playing Puss after accepting the role, which had determined Puss's personality.<ref name=IndieLondon2>{{cite web|url=http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Film-Review/puss-in-boots-antonio-banderas-interview|title=Puss in Boots \u2013 Antonio Banderas interview|last=Carnevale|first=Rob|website=IndieLondon|access-date=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702140756/http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Film-Review/puss-in-boots-antonio-banderas-interview|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Although he could have used a high-pitched voice for Puss, which was the filmmakers' original idea,<ref name=ETCanada/> he and the others working on the film opted for a tone that was \"deeper\" and \"more breathy\" than his normal voice.<ref name=Collider2/><ref name=IndieLondon2/> Banderas called the choice \"very interesting\", adding that it \"helped to establish the limits and the parameters of the character in terms of personality\".<ref name=IndieLondon2/> He regarded the effect as \"almost like a lion trapped in the body of a little cat\", which makes Puss \"different\".<ref name=IndieLondon2/> According to the actor, Puss's voice contrasts with his body; he stated that \"the cat is not supposed to talk like that\", adding that the difference between Puss's voice and appearance is [[comic relief]].<ref name=Collider2/> He also commented that the contrast between Puss's appearance and voice makes it seem like he is not even aware of his size.<ref name=ETCanada/> Banderas said that after the decision about Puss's voice had been made, the filmmakers had begun depicting the character \"in a totally different way\".<ref name=IndieLondon2/> He added that Puss had initially been conceptualized as \"quite a little character\" but had started gaining more importance after the filmmakers had realized his potential.<ref name=IndieLondon2/> Banderas said that he and the filmmakers had \"a lot of fun\" with Puss's character, and felt that viewers did too.<ref name=Collider3/>\n\n[[File:Puss_in_Boots_from_Shrek_Forever_After.png|thumb|left|Puss in Boots in ''[[Shrek Forever After]]'' (2010). Antonio Banderas joked that Puss gaining weight did not bother him but the pink ribbon around his neck did.<ref name=RTE/>|alt=A plumper Puss in Boots]]\nBanderas said that the first scene he had recorded was coughing up a [[hairball]], adding that he had spent \"45 minutes doing strange sounds\";<ref name=RTE>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2010/0617/422965-banderasa/|title=Antonio Banderas Interview|date=June 17, 2010|website=[[RT\u00c9.ie]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630141348/https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2010/0617/422965-banderasa/|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=TheNewYorkTimes/> although it left him voiceless,<ref name=RTE/><ref name=TheNewYorkTimes/> he saw the moment as \"fun\".<ref name=RTE/> When asked about the most difficult part of voicing Puss, Banderas said \"the biggest challenge was to understand the animation process\".<ref name=RTE/> The actor said that in addition to providing Puss's English voice, he voiced the character in [[Mexican Spanish]], [[Castilian Spanish]], and Italian, calling the Italian [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dub]] \"the most challenging\" since he had to follow \"the character's face movement\";<ref name=RTE/> Puss speaks with a lisp in the Spanish dub.<ref name=RTE/> When he was at the Cannes Film Festival for ''Shrek 2'', Banderas noticed that Puss's character received much public attention.<ref name=IndieLondon2/> About Puss's changed appearance in ''[[Shrek Forever After]]'' (2010), Banderas joked that the character's weight gain did not bother him but the pink ribbon (which Puss wears in the film) did. For ''Puss in Boots'', Banderas advised the filmmakers to depict the relation between Puss and [[Kitty Softpaws]] (voiced by [[Salma Hayek]]) as a \"love-hate\" relationship to generate \"a great lot of comedy\";<ref name=RTE/> Hayek stated that Banderas is completely believable as Puss since both are \"very self-confident\", characterizing him as perfect for this role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/movies/puss-in-boots-is-not-the-cat-s-meow-1.3274833|title='Puss in Boots' is not the cat's meow|date=October 26, 2011|last=Guzm\u00e1n|first=Rafer|newspaper=[[Newsday]]|access-date=June 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610180933/https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/movies/puss-in-boots-is-not-the-cat-s-meow-1.3274833|archive-date=June 10, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Banderas said that he wanted Puss to keep \"his mischievousness and edginess\" in this film since viewers enjoyed \"the edgy side\" of the character.<ref name=RTE/>\n\nAsked about similarities between him and Puss, Banderas said that Puss had values which he lacked; the character was \"too courageous\".<ref name=IndieLondon2/> He said that the filmmakers had wanted to incorporate some of his \"personal features\" into Puss's character, with characters he had played in other films, such as Zorro and the characters he had portrayed in ''[[Desperado (film)|Desperado]]'' (1995) and ''[[The 13th Warrior]]'' (1999), serving as inspirations.<ref name=IndieLondon2/> Banderas said that he saw \"a little bit more\" of himself as the films in which Puss appears were released,<ref name=IndieLondon2/> describing Puss as his \"alter ego\".<ref name=TheTelegraph/> He is proud that his character is Latino since it is \"good for diversity and cultural interaction\", saying children would see that \"heroes actually have a strong accent\" in ''Puss in Boots''.<ref name=Collider2/>\n\nBanderas said that he loved Puss's character.<ref name=IndieLondon2/> Asked about which one of Puss's characteristics he preferred, the actor cited his mischievousness; according to Banderas, Puss does amazing things in the three ''Shrek'' films in which he appears. Playing Puss meant \"a lot\" for his career;<ref name=RTE/> although he had not been able to speak English when he had come to America, the filmmakers wanted his voice for the films.<ref name=RTE/><ref name=TheNewYorkTimes/> Banderas said he had not initially known how difficult voicing a character was, stating that \"you have to get into the character\" to do it well.<ref name=RTE/> The ''Shrek'' franchise was important to him, representing \"the magnificent part of Hollywood and the search for perfection\";<ref name=RTE/> Banderas viewed being a part of the ''Shrek'' production as \"very beautiful\".<ref name=RTE/> He was recognized in public for his role as Puss.<ref name=TheNewYorkTimes/>\n\n[[Eric Bauza]] voiced Puss in the [[Netflix]] series ''The Adventures of Puss in Boots''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-31990396|title=Antonio Banderas: Puss, Pirate and Picasso|date=March 26, 2015|last=Geoghegan|first=Kev|website=[[BBC]]|access-date=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730202724/https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-31990396|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=Collider4>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/puss-in-boots-season-6-release-date-clip/|title=Exclusive: The End of the World Is Nigh in 'The Adventures of Puss in Boots' Clip|date=January 24, 2018|last=Trumbore|first=Dave|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706123707/http://collider.com/puss-in-boots-season-6-release-date-clip/|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2015/01/05/Eric-Bauza-to-lend-his-voice-to-the-feline-star-of-Netflixs-Puss-in-Boots-series/1731420508723/|title=Eric Bauza to lend his voice to the feline star of Netflix's 'Puss in Boots' series|date=January 5, 2015|last=Butler|first=Karen|website=[[United Press International]]|access-date=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730203424/https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2015/01/05/Eric-Bauza-to-lend-his-voice-to-the-feline-star-of-Netflixs-Puss-in-Boots-series/1731420508723/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bauza said that he had auditioned \"fair and square\" for Puss's role (despite having worked with executive producer Doug Langdale on another show) and had enjoyed working with the production team.<ref name=Collider5>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/the-adventures-of-puss-in-boots-eric-bauza-interivew/|title=Eric Bauza Talks The Adventures of Puss in Boots|date=February 1, 2015|last=Radish|first=Christina|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|access-date=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730175520/http://collider.com/the-adventures-of-puss-in-boots-eric-bauza-interivew/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He said he had been asked to do a [[motion capture]] as Puss before the start of the series, adding that \"to embody that character, physically, was so tough\".<ref name=Collider5/> Bauza called the sounds he needed to provide for Puss \"iconic\" since he is \"such a well-known character\".<ref name=Collider5/> According to Bauza, voicing Puss was a \"challenge because Puss speaks in such a whisper\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2015/01/17/features/a-mishmash-of-family-fun-and-news-101/|title=A mishmash of family fun and news|date=January 17, 2015|newspaper=[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]]|access-date=August 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828130233/http://www.staradvertiser.com/2015/01/17/features/a-mishmash-of-family-fun-and-news-101/|archive-date=August 28, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bauza said that he had \"watched a lot of Antonio's films\", had imagined how he would have performed on certain occasions, and had tried to be as \"unpredictable\";<ref name=Collider5/> he stated that his voice is similar to Banderas's. Since he voiced the central character in the series, Bauza had \"the luck and luxury to be able to record with a majority of the people that are in the show\".<ref name=Collider5/> He felt that \"having the responsibility of taking over a role such as Puss in Boots is quite the honor\".<ref name=Collider5/> Bauza thought that a series centered on Puss was clever, maintaining the audience interested until the release of ''Puss in Boots 2'', and said it would present \"some sides to Puss that you [cannot] really get out of the feature films or even shorts\".<ref name=Collider5/> [[Andr\u00e9 Sogliuzzo]] voiced Puss in several [[Shrek video games|''Shrek'' video games]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/characters/Shrek/Puss-In-Boots/|title=Puss in Boots|website=Behind The Voice Actors|access-date=July 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708155118/https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/characters/Shrek/Puss-In-Boots/|archive-date=July 8, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[meow]]ing [[Sound effect|sounds]] Puss makes in the films were provided by [[Frank Welker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timescolonist.com/entertainment/television/small-screen-voice-over-acting-nice-work-if-you-can-get-it-1.23385869|title=Small Screen: Voice-over acting nice work if you can get it|date=August 1, 2018|last=Lee|first=Luaine|newspaper=[[Times Colonist]]|access-date=September 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920225341/https://www.timescolonist.com/entertainment/television/small-screen-voice-over-acting-nice-work-if-you-can-get-it-1.23385869|archive-date=September 20, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Characterization===\nMiller characterized Puss as \"a fiercely loyal and honorable cat\".<ref name=Collider/> He further referred to Puss as \"a pint-sized, pocket-sized, fun character\".<ref name=Collider/> Miller also described Puss as \"really appealing\" and also as \"a normally proportioned cat dressed up, but bold, animated, and romantic\".<ref name=FantasyMagazine/> He viewed Puss as \"colorful\" as well.<ref name=ComicBookResources/> Miller stated that \"Antonio's persona and this explosive, dynamic, huge figure that was really cute\" completely fit Puss's portrayal in ''Puss in Boots''.<ref name=Collider/> He also said Puss is an \"amplified version of Antonio coming out of this tiny little fury package\" and that this makes him an \"instantly funny\", \"intriguing\", and \"complex character\".<ref name=Quickflix/> He added that Puss \"is very melodramatic\", seeing this as \"funny\" because of how Puss's character is depicted and believing Banderas was \"really good\" at portraying this side of the character.<ref name=Collider/> He further said Puss \"is at his funniest when he takes himself too seriously\", which always happens since he \"sees himself as a very important figure\".<ref name=FantasyMagazine/> Miller stated that while Puss has a \"really big heart\", he still is somewhat mischievous.<ref name=FantasyMagazine/> Miller characterized Puss as someone who had seen \"the light really early in life\" and who is \"affecting change on everyone around him\".<ref name=WeGotThisCovered>{{cite web|url=http://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/interview-chris-miller-puss-boots/|title=Exclusive Interview With Chris Miller on Puss in Boots|year=2011|last=Tatum|first=Billy|website=We Got This Covered|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630132826/http://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/interview-chris-miller-puss-boots/|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He further described him as \"half lover, half fighter\" and as \"a bit roguish and a bit of a troublemaker\".<ref name=WeGotThisCovered/> Miller also characterized Puss as \"unpredictable\".<ref name=AnimationWorldNetwork2>{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/chris-miller-talks-puss-boots|title=Chris Miller Talks 'Puss in Boots'|date=October 28, 2011|last=Desowitz|first=Bill|website=[[Animation World Network]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630133225/https://www.awn.com/animationworld/chris-miller-talks-puss-boots|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nLangdale said that Puss is a \"character anyone can relate to\", which makes him \"great\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2015/01/first-look-dreamworks-netflix-original-the-adventures-of-puss-in-boots-123715/|title=First Look: Dreamworks' Netflix Original \"The Adventures of Puss In Boots\"|date=January 5, 2015|last=Beck|first=Jerry|website=[[IndieWire]]|access-date=June 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630142716/https://www.indiewire.com/2015/01/first-look-dreamworks-netflix-original-the-adventures-of-puss-in-boots-123715/|archive-date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Jerry Beck}}</ref> He said that \"on the surface, Puss is the coolest guy in the world\", \"great at everything\", \"saves and protects people\", and \"seems like he can defeat anyone\", despite \"this wonderful vulnerability\" due to him being \"tiny\".<ref name=SpinSouthWest/> According to Langdale, Puss is \"just a regular-sized cat in a people-sized world\" with an \"elephant-sized\" personality.<ref name=SpinSouthWest/>\n\nBanderas described Puss as \"a little bit mysterious\", with \"a sweetness\";<ref name=TheTelegraph/> he added that the character \"knows how to make people jealous\" and \"can be manipulative with just his eyes\".<ref name=TheTelegraph/> According to Banderas, viewers could identify with Puss's attempts to obtain something.<ref name=TheTelegraph/> Banderas said that Puss is a \"womanizer\" who courts \"the lady cats\",<ref name=RTE/> and enjoys having a female \"in front of him that can fight as hard as him\".<ref name=IndieLondon2/> He stated that Puss is \"so little\", and the actor enjoyed his \"contrast in size\" with [[Shrek (character)|Shrek]].<ref name=RTE/>\n\n==Appearances==\n===''Shrek 2''===\n{{main|Shrek 2}}\nPuss makes his first appearance as a [[supporting character]] in the film ''Shrek 2'',<ref name=AnimationWorldNetwork/> where he is initially hired by the [[List of Shrek characters#King Harold|father]] of [[Princess Fiona]] (Shrek's wife) to kill Shrek. He meets Shrek and his companion, [[Donkey (Shrek)|Donkey]], and unsuccessfully attacks Shrek. Puss tells Shrek the reason for his attack and begs for mercy. Because Shrek spares his life, Puss offers to join him and becomes his partner. During the course of the film, Puss helps Shrek to obtain a potion that turns Shrek and Fiona into humans, attacks a group of guards to buy Shrek time to save Fiona, and befriends Shrek and Donkey. At the end of the film, Puss sings a [[duet]] with Donkey.<ref name=Variety/><ref name=Empire/><ref name=TheGuardian/>\n\n===''Shrek the Third''===\n{{main|Shrek the Third}}\nIn the film ''[[Shrek the Third]]'' (2007), Puss travels with Shrek and Donkey to bring Fiona's cousin, [[List of Shrek characters#Arthur Pendragon|Arthur Pendragon]], to the Far Far Away Kingdom so he can become the new king (instead of Shrek). During their journey, Puss gives Shrek advice. In a later [[teleportation]] spell, Puss has his body switched with Donkey's. After initial difficulty getting used to their new bodies, Puss and Donkey join forces in the battle against [[List of Shrek characters#Prince Charming|Prince Charming]] to save Shrek, and they convince Arthur that he is meant to be king. Puss and Donkey regain their own bodies and, in an end-of-film [[Ellipsis (narrative device)|ellipsis]], Puss and other characters care for Shrek and Fiona's [[List of Shrek characters#Farkle, Fergus and Felicia|children]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/6550/shrek-the-third-review|title=Shrek The Third: review|date=July 2, 2007|last=Mclaughlin|first=Robert|magazine=[[Den of Geek]]|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704002816/http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/6550/shrek-the-third-review|archive-date=July 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/18/movies/18shre.html|title=A Grumpy Green Giant Who Would Not Be King|date=May 18, 2007|last=Scott|first=A. O.|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706084732/https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/18/movies/18shre.html|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=A. O. Scott}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/05/18/shrek-the-third|title=Shrek the Third|date=May 17, 2007|author=Stax|website=[[IGN]]|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706093521/http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/05/18/shrek-the-third|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===''Shrek Forever After''===\n{{main|Shrek Forever After}}\nPuss is present in the film ''Shrek Forever After'', at the beginning of which he attends the first birthday party of Shrek and Fiona's children. In the [[Parallel universes in fiction|alternate universe]] created by the film's [[antagonist]], [[List of Shrek characters#Rumpelstiltskin|Rumpelstiltskin]], and entered by Shrek, Puss has gained weight and is Fiona's [[pet]] after his retirement. Realizing that Shrek and Fiona have feelings for each other, Puss becomes Shrek's friend. When Shrek, Fiona, and the other ogres in this universe are captured at Rumpelstiltskin's behest, Puss and Donkey save Shrek and Fiona; Puss is a key participant in the later battle against Rumpelstiltskin and his allies. Shrek returns to the real universe, where Puss (as his usual self) enjoys the birthday party with the other characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/jul/01/shrek-forever-after-film-review|title=Shrek Forever After|date=July 1, 2010|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704001126/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/jul/01/shrek-forever-after-film-review|archive-date=July 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Peter Bradshaw}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/shrek-forever/review/|title=Shrek Forever After Review|date=June 1, 2010|last=White|first=James|magazine=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|access-date=July 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704013649/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/shrek-forever/review/|archive-date=July 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2010/05/21/shrek-forever-after-3/|title=Shrek Forever After|date=May 21, 2010|last=Schwarzbaum|first=Lisa|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=September 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921003224/https://ew.com/article/2010/05/21/shrek-forever-after-3/|archive-date=September 21, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Lisa Schwarzbaum}}</ref>\n\n===''Puss in Boots''===\n{{main|Puss in Boots (2011 film)}}\nThe film ''Puss in Boots'' is a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] from, and [[prequel]] to, the ''Shrek'' films.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2011/10/28/feline-less-than-groovy/|title=Feline less than groovy|date=October 28, 2011|last=Lumenick|first=Lou|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|access-date=August 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829171509/https://nypost.com/2011/10/28/feline-less-than-groovy/|archive-date=August 29, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|author-link=Lou Lumenick}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/75089-guillermo-del-toro-adds-puss-in-boots-cameo|title=Guillermo del Toro Adds Puss in Boots Cameo|date=March 9, 2011|last=Lesnick|first=Silas|website=[[CraveOnline#Owned or associated websites|ComingSoon]]|access-date=August 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829182222/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/75089-guillermo-del-toro-adds-puss-in-boots-cameo|archive-date=August 29, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=TheIndependent/> It begins by presenting Puss's [[Pseudonym|aliases]], including \"Diablo Gato\",<ref name=Aliases1>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/risky-business/antonio-banderas-salma-hayek-bring-187435|title=Antonio Banderas, Salma Hayek Bring 'Puss in Boots' to France (Cannes)|date=May 11, 2011|last=Fernandez|first=Jay A.|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=September 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920232447/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/risky-business/antonio-banderas-salma-hayek-bring-187435|archive-date=September 20, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"The Furry Lover\",<ref name=Aliases1/> \"Chupacabra\",<ref name=Aliases1/> \"Frisky Two Times\",<ref name=Aliases2>{{cite web|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2011/10/27/puss-in-boots-is-a-purr-fect-family-film-2/|title='Puss in Boots' is a purr-fect family film|date=October 27, 2011|last=Moore|first=Roger|newspaper=[[Orange County Register]]|access-date=September 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920233229/https://www.ocregister.com/2011/10/27/puss-in-boots-is-a-purr-fect-family-film-2/|archive-date=September 20, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and \"The Ginger Hit Man\".<ref name=Aliases2/> After he was abandoned when he was little, Puss finds shelter at an orphanage in the town of San Ricardo and is adopted by [[List of Shrek characters#Imelda|Imelda]]. He becomes friends with [[List of Shrek characters#Humpty Dumpty|Humpty Alexander Dumpty]], who gives him the name \"Puss\" and with whom he decides to find the magic beans that would bring them to the [[List of Shrek characters#Golden Goose|Golden Goose]] (which lays golden eggs). Puss performs a heroic act, for which he receives acclaim and his boots. His bond with Humpty begins to fray, and Humpty compels Puss to (unknowingly) rob a bank with him. Puss leaves San Ricardo; years later, he learns who owns the magic beans and plans to steal them. He meets a cat who also wants to steal them: Kitty Softpaws, Humpty's partner. Humpty asks Puss to join them in their search for the beans, and Puss eventually accepts. They find the beans, plant them, and a beanstalk brings them to a castle in the sky. They find the Golden Goose and return with it to the ground. Puss returns to San Ricardo, where he realizes that Humpty has been plotting against him. Puss is arrested, and he learns that the [[List of Shrek characters#Great Terror|Golden Goose's mother]] will come and try to retrieve it. With Kitty's help, Puss escapes, goes to Humpty, and they reconcile. Humpty sacrifices himself to allow Puss to save the Golden Goose and return it to its mother (preventing the town's destruction), and Puss and Kitty escape the town guards.<ref name=IGN2/><ref name=TheHollywoodReporter2/><ref name=AXS2/>\n\n==={{anchor|Other}}Other appearances===\nPuss is present in the [[short film]] ''[[Shrek (franchise)#Far Far Away Idol|Far Far Away Idol]]'' (2004), singing a part of the song \"[[These Boots Are Made for Walking]]\";<ref name=BBC>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/10/28/shrek_2_se_2004_dvd_review.shtml|title=Shrek 2: Special Edition DVD (2004)|last=Papamichael|first=Stella|website=[[BBC]]|access-date=September 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903181932/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/10/28/shrek_2_se_2004_dvd_review.shtml|archive-date=September 3, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=AnimationTrip>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationtrip.com/item.php?id=223|title=Shrek 2, the Record Shattering $439 Million Box Office Smash Premieres on DVD and VHS Friday, November 5|website=[[Odyssey Productions|Animation Trip]]|access-date=September 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903184014/http://www.animationtrip.com/item.php?id=223|archive-date=September 3, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> he also appears in his own [[music video]] of this song.<ref name=BBC/><ref name=AnimationTrip/> Puss is present in the [[television special]] ''[[Shrek the Halls]]'' (2007), going with other characters to Shrek's home to celebrate [[Christmas]] and telling a Christmas story.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/03/shrek-the-halls-dvd-review|title=Shrek the Halls DVD Review|date=November 3, 2008|last=Vargo|first=Jason P.|website=[[IGN]]|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706121202/http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/03/shrek-the-halls-dvd-review|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2016/12/shrek-the-halls-2016-what-time-does-the-abc-special-air-cast-on-tonight/|title='Shrek The Halls' 2016: What Time Does the ABC Special Air?|date=December 8, 2016|last=Levine|first=Daniel S.|website=[[Heavy.com]]|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706114943/https://heavy.com/entertainment/2016/12/shrek-the-halls-2016-what-time-does-the-abc-special-air-cast-on-tonight/|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://weartv.com/news/local/abc-celebrates-holidays-with-25-days-of-christmas|title=ABC celebrates holidays with \"25 Days of Christmas\"|date=November 22, 2017|last=Zamora|first=Candice|website=[[WEAR-TV|WEAR]]|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706120434/http://weartv.com/news/local/abc-celebrates-holidays-with-25-days-of-christmas|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He also appears in the television special ''[[Scared Shrekless]]'' (2010), participating in a [[storytelling]] contest to frighten Shrek on [[Halloween]]; Puss tells a story with Donkey, but they cannot agree on a version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/kecks-exclusives-look-1023773/|title=Keck's Exclusives: First Look at Scared Shrekless|date=September 29, 2010|last=Keck|first=William|magazine=[[TV Guide]]|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706100120/http://www.tvguide.com/news/kecks-exclusives-look-1023773/|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.romper.com/p/9-best-family-halloween-movies-on-netflix-21206|title=9 Best Family Halloween Movies on Netflix|date=October 27, 2016|last=Johnson|first=Angela|website=Romper|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706111434/https://www.romper.com/p/9-best-family-halloween-movies-on-netflix-21206|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/top/3421/21/Ghostbusters-1983-21-family-friendly-Halloween-movies-TV-shows-you-can-find-on-Netflix-Amazon.html|title=21 family-friendly Halloween movies & TV shows you can find on Netflix & Amazon|date=October 22, 2015|website=Desert News|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706111836/https://www.deseretnews.com/top/3421/21/Ghostbusters-1983-21-family-friendly-Halloween-movies-TV-shows-you-can-find-on-Netflix-Amazon.html|archive-date=July 6, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Puss appears in the short film ''[[Shrek (franchise)#Donkey's Caroling Christmas-tacular|Donkey's Caroling Christmas-tacular]]'' (2010), singing his version of the song \"[[Feliz Navidad (song)|Feliz Navidad]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01pnjsx|title=Donkey's Caroling Christmas-tacular|website=[[BBC]]|access-date=September 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903204856/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01pnjsx|archive-date=September 3, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Puss is also present in the short film ''[[Shrek (franchise)#Thriller Night|Thriller Night]]'' (2011), in which a [[zombie]] version of him is shown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20111021005262/en/ADDING-MULTIMEDIA-Hulu-Coming-Nintendo-Systems-Nintendo|title=Adding Multimedia Hulu Plus Coming to Nintendo Systems as Nintendo 3DS Preps for 3D Video Recording|date=October 21, 2011|website=[[Business Wire]]|access-date=September 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903193330/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20111021005262/en/ADDING-MULTIMEDIA-Hulu-Coming-Nintendo-Systems-Nintendo|archive-date=September 3, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He also appears in the short film ''[[Puss in Boots: The Three Diablos]]'' (2012), training three kittens and leading them to the right path.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/puss-in-boots-blu-ray-review/|title=Puss in Boots Blu-ray Review|date=April 1, 2012|last=Dellamorte|first=Andre|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|access-date=July 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706112216/http: